HEADWORD: collards
<hw>col"lards</hw> <pr>(k⟦ocr⟧l"l⟦etil⟧rdz)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>
<ety>[Corrupted fr. <ets>colewort</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Young
cabbage, used as ⟦ldquo⟧greens⟦rdquo⟧; esp. the leaves of a kind of kale
(<spn>Brassica oleracea</spn> <varn>acephala</varn>) cultivated for that
purpose, the collard or colewort.</def> <mark>[Colloq. Southern U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. -- </b>collard greens.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of kale (<spn>Brassica oleracea</spn>
<varn>acephala</varn>) cultivated in the southern United States as a
vegetable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Collared</ent>⟦br⟧
